  "prompt": "English Grammar: Which is more Grammatically Correct - \"I wish I was there\" OR \"I wish I were there\"?",
  "response": "\"I wish I were there\" is generally considered more grammatically correct, especially in formal writing.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Subjunctive Mood:** The phrase \"I wish...\" introduces a subjunctive mood, which expresses a hypothetical or unreal situation. In the subjunctive mood, the verb \"to be\" takes the form \"were\" for all persons (I, you, he, she, it, we, they).\n\n*   **Formal vs. Informal:** While \"I wish I was there\" is commonly used in informal speech and writing, it's not traditionally considered grammatically correct. It's often seen as a simplification of the subjunctive mood.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   **\"I wish I were there\"** - Grammatically correct and preferred in formal contexts.\n\n*   **\"I wish I was there\"** - Acceptable in informal contexts, but not traditionally considered grammatically correct.",
